1. Add logic to detect when an operand is a `select` that behaves as `A & B` (i.e., `select A, B, false`) or `A | B` (`select A, true, B`).
2. Canonicalize such selects into the same form handled by the existing `(A & B) ^ (A | C)` logic.
3. Reuse the existing optimization path once matching is successful.

This aligns with LLVM’s canonicalization and folding principles: recognize semantic equivalents of logical operations and reduce them to a known pattern.

The change will be inserted just before the existing `(A & B) ^ (A | C)` matcher, adding equivalent matching logic for `select`-based logical operations. We preserve `OneUse` constraints to ensure legality and avoid introducing unnecessary copies.

